body:
## Summary

When an interface contains multiple `initial` blocks and a method is called on that interface, Verilator may produce an internal error: "Duplicate declaration of member name: ''" due to the VMemberMap attempting to insert multiple anonymous nodes (which have empty names) into its internal map.

## Minimal Reproduction

```systemverilog
interface my_iface;
   int value;

   // Multiple initial blocks (anonymous - have empty names)
   initial value = 0;
   initial $display("Init 1");
   initial $display("Init 2");

   // A method that triggers member map lookup
   function int get_value();
      return value;
   endfunction
endinterface

module t;
   my_iface iface();
   initial begin
      if (iface.get_value() !== 0) $stop;
      $write("*-* All Finished *-*\n");
      $finish;
   end
endmodule
```

## Root Cause

In `V3MemberMap.h`, the `memberInsert()` function inserts child nodes into a map keyed by name. When multiple anonymous nodes (like `initial` blocks) are processed, they all have empty names `""`, causing the second insertion to fail with a "Duplicate declaration" error.

## Proposed Fix

Add a check to skip nodes with empty names in `memberInsert()`, since these cannot be looked up by name anyway:

```cpp
void memberInsert(MemberMap& mmapr, AstNode* childp, bool warn = true) {
    // Skip nodes without names (e.g., initial blocks, anonymous statements)
    // These can't be looked up by name anyway
    if (childp->name().empty()) return;
    const auto mitPair = mmapr.emplace(childp->name(), childp);
    // ...
}
```

## IEEE Reference

IEEE 1800-2017 Section 25.3 allows multiple initial blocks in interfaces.

